Title: MAGIC HOUR
Credit: written by
Author: Joshua Brooks
Draft date: First Draft — December 2014
Notes: A coming-of-age drama. Los Angeles, December 2014. Long takes, natural light, practical locations. No narration. No speeches. Let scenes breathe past the point of comfort.
Contact: —

/* DIRECTION NOTE: The city is the second lead. Every location should be photographed the way you'd photograph a face — patiently, in available light, without comment. When in doubt, hold the shot four seconds longer than feels safe. */

FADE IN:

EXT. CAMINO SCHOOL — OJAI, CALIFORNIA — MORNING

Oak trees. Mist burning off the hills. An expensive boarding school doing an impression of a ranch: white fences, adobe buildings, a bell that hasn't rung for anything real in eighty years.

A pond. Beside the pond, a new teak BENCH with a fresh rectangle of bare wood where a plaque used to be. Four screw holes.

MILES CALDER, 17, sits on a duffel bag outside the administration building. Sharp-faced, watchful, wearing a school blazer with the crest half picked-off — threads hanging where the emblem used to be, a project of many bored weeks. He is reading a paperback he is not reading. His eyes are on the bench.

Through the window behind him, half-audible, the DEAN on the phone:

DEAN (O.S.)
(muffled, through glass)
— we've left two messages with the mother, the letter went out Friday — no, he's being driven to the bus this morning — Mrs. Calder travels for work, I understand, but at a certain point —

A GROUNDSKEEPER passes, pushing a cart. He nods at Miles. Miles nods back. They know each other. It's the only warm exchange this campus has left for him.

A Volvo pulls up. MR. HODGES, 50s, history teacher, the kind of man who means well in a way that has never once helped anyone, leans over and pushes open the passenger door.

MR. HODGES
Ojai station. Chariot awaits.

Miles stands, shoulders the duffel. He looks back once — not at the school. At the bench. Four screw holes.

He gets in the car.

INT. MR. HODGES' VOLVO — MOVING — HIGHWAY 33 — MORNING

Winding road out of the valley. Golden hills, live oaks. Mr. Hodges drives like a man who has read about driving.

MR. HODGES
You know what I keep coming back to? You had a 4.1 as a sophomore.

MILES
(looking out the window)
Yeah, that guy was great.

MR. HODGES
The board would've worked with you. Even after the assembly thing. Even after the grades. If you'd just — the plaque, Miles. Why the plaque?

Miles watches the hills go by. There's a long guardrail section coming up — new, brighter metal than the rail around it, maybe forty feet of it, patched into the old rail like a scar.

Miles watches the new section of guardrail approach, pass, and go.

MILES
(quietly)
It had his name spelled wrong.

MR. HODGES
(beat)
What?

MILES
The plaque. "Samuel Ortegas." With an S. Eleven months, nobody noticed. It was solid brass, though. Really nice brass.

Mr. Hodges opens his mouth. Closes it. Drives.

MR. HODGES
(finally, gently, uselessly)
They would have fixed the plaque.

MILES
(still looking out the window)
Yeah.

EXT. OJAI — BUS STOP — MORNING

The Volvo idles. Miles gets out with the duffel. Mr. Hodges leans across the seat one last time:

MR. HODGES
The 101 connector gets you to the Amtrak in Ventura, then it's two hours to Union Station. Your mother's picking you up downtown?

MILES
(shouldering the bag; the lie arriving smooth and pre-assembled)
Yeah. She took the day.

MR. HODGES
Good. That's good.
(beat; he wants a moment; Miles does not give him one)
Read the Didion I gave you.

MILES
I will.

He won't. The Volvo pulls away. Miles stands alone at the bus stop in the December light. He takes out his phone — an iPhone 5, cracked screen — and looks at it.

INSERT — PHONE: a text thread with "MOM." Her last message, three days ago: "Denver til Sat!! Conference is endless. June w/ Grandma after school. Home Sat night, get a ride from the Hendersons Saturday? Love you." Two hearts.

Miles types: "yeah all good. school stuff til sat." Sends it.

He looks at the sent message for a moment. Then he pockets the phone, and looks down the empty road toward the 101, toward Los Angeles, toward four days that belong to no one.

The bus appears, far off, shimmering in the road heat.

INT. AMTRAK PACIFIC SURFLINER — MOVING — DAY

The ocean out the left-side windows, silver and enormous. Miles, forehead against the glass. Across the aisle, a WOMAN, 30s, laptop open to Final Draft, screenplay format unmistakable. She types, deletes, types the same line again.

Miles watches her cursor blink. She catches him.

SCREENWRITER
(not unfriendly)
It's a pilot.

MILES
Sorry.

SCREENWRITER
Don't be. Someone should watch it.

She goes back to typing. Miles goes back to the ocean. Neither smiles. It wasn't a joke. It was information.

EXT. UNION STATION — LOS ANGELES — AFTERNOON

The great hall doors. Miles comes out into the light with the duffel, and the film gives us our first real look at it: LOS ANGELES, December 2014, seventy-one degrees, the palms on Alameda backlit and dusty, the sky that particular smoggy gold that photographs like a filter and feels like nothing at all.

Miles stands there. Seventeen, expelled, invisible, four days of runway.

Nobody in the entire city knows where he is. Watch his face discover that this is the best feeling he's had in a year, and that it is also, in the exact same instant, the loneliest.

INT./EXT. UBERX — TOYOTA CAMRY — MOVING — AFTERNOON

A phone mounted on the dash runs the Uber driver app, 2014 edition. Behind the wheel: DEREK, 29, friendly in a caffeinated way, a USC lanyard on the rearview he did not earn at USC.

DEREK
Miles? For Hollywood?

MILES
(getting in back)
Yeah.

DEREK
You can sit up front, man, it's not a taxi. That's the whole thing. It's the future.

Miles stays in the back. Derek pulls out anyway, undiscouraged.

DEREK (CONT'D)
Visiting? You look like you're visiting.

MILES
I live here. Sort of. My mom's in Mar Vista.

DEREK
But you're going to a motel on Sunset.

MILES
(beat)
Family's remodeling.

DEREK
(nodding at the mirror; not believing him; not caring; LA)
Cool, cool.

They merge onto the 101 North. The downtown towers slide past, then the murals, then the endless specific everything of the city.

DEREK (CONT'D)
You want the aux? I got Spotify premium. No ads.

MILES
I'm okay.

DEREK
(driving; then, because no one in this city can hold it in past ninety seconds)
I'm actually a writer. Driving's temporary. Everyone says that, I know, but I've got a thing that's basically almost happening — it's like "Drive" meets "Her," it's about a guy who drives for one of these apps, right, and he falls in love with the dispatch algorithm —

MILES
(despite himself)
Does she love him back?

DEREK
(delighted; smacking the wheel)
THAT'S THE MOVIE. That's the question. See — you get it. Nobody gets it.
(fishing in the console, one hand, handing back a business card)
I do script coverage too. Ten bucks a pop. You know anyone.

Miles takes the card. DEREK KOWALCZYK — WRITER / COVERAGE / RIDES. A gmail address.

Miles looks at it, then out the window, where the Hollywood sign has just appeared between two buildings, small and white and far, exactly like every photograph of it, which is somehow the surprising part — that it's really there, being itself, all day.

EXT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — SUNSET BOULEVARD, EAST HOLLYWOOD — LATE AFTERNOON

A two-story stucco L around a parking lot. A sign from 1962: GOLD STAR MOTEL — COLOR TV — WEEKLY. The Camry pulls away. Miles stands with his duffel under the sign.

INT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — OFFICE — CONTINUOUS

Plexiglass. A MANAGER, 60s, watches a Lakers pregame show on a TV wedged next to a fan.

MANAGER
How many nights.

MILES
Four. Maybe five.

MANAGER
ID.

Miles slides his school ID under the plexiglass — a laminated card with the Camino crest and a photo of a younger, softer him.

MANAGER (CONT'D)
This is a student ID.

MILES
It's all I've got. I can pay cash. Up front.

The manager looks at him for a long moment. At the duffel. At the blazer with the picked-off crest. He's seen this exact kid four hundred times. Every version of what happens next has already happened here.

MANAGER
(sliding a form under the glass)
No parties. No guests after ten. Ice machine's broken since the earthquake.

MILES
Which earthquake?

MANAGER
(turning back to the pregame)
Pick one.

INT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — ROOM 24 — EVENING

A queen bed with a floral spread. A painting of a harbor no one has ever visited. The COLOR TV, true to the sign's promise. Miles sets the duffel down and sits on the end of the bed.

The room hums. Traffic on Sunset through the window, and a slice of pink sky between buildings going neon-blue at the edges.

He unzips the duffel. Clothes. The Didion paperback, unread. And — wrapped in a T-shirt, heavy — the PLAQUE. Solid brass. "IN MEMORY OF SAMUEL ORTEGAS '15 — FOREVER IN OUR HEARTS."

Ortegas. With an S.

Miles sets it on the nightstand, propped against the lamp, facing the bed. He looks at it the way you look at a roommate.

MILES
(to the plaque; conversational; this is clearly not the first time)
Well. We made it.

He falls back on the bed, arms out, and the neon from the liquor store across the street comes through the curtain and moves on the ceiling, red, then blue, then red.

EXT. SUNSET BOULEVARD — EAST HOLLYWOOD — NIGHT

Miles walks. The film walks with him — a long, patient tracking shot, the first of many: donut shop, botánica, 24-hour laundromat, a man selling roses at a red light to cars with their windows up.

He passes a BUS STOP where an ACTRESS'S FACE, forty feet wide, smiles down from a billboard for a network procedural. Beneath it, on the bench, a MAN sleeps under a moving blanket, his shopping cart docked beside him like a car.

Miles stops. Looks at the billboard. Looks at the man. Nobody else on the street finds this composition remarkable, and their not-finding-it-remarkable is the thing Miles can't stop looking at. He takes out his phone. Frames a photo of the billboard and the bench together.

Doesn't take it.

Puts the phone away and keeps walking.

INT. ASTRO FAMILY RESTAURANT — DINER — SILVER LAKE — NIGHT

A googie-architecture diner, orange booths, mostly empty at 10 PM. Miles in a window booth with a hamburger and the Didion, still unread, deployed as a shield.

A WAITRESS, 50s, warm, refills his coffee unasked.

WAITRESS
School night?

MILES
I'm homeschooled.

WAITRESS
(deadpan)
Aren't we all.

She moves off. In the next booth, back-to-back with Miles: two FILM STUDENTS, 20s, one gesturing with a fork.

FILM STUDENT #1
— because everything's content now. That's the thing. It's not movies anymore, it's content. There's a kid — I'm serious — there's a kid who films himself scaring his roommate, that's the whole channel, he scares his roommate, and he has more viewers than "Boyhood" had in theaters —

FILM STUDENT #2
"Boyhood" doesn't want viewers. "Boyhood" wants believers.

FILM STUDENT #1
What does that MEAN? You keep saying stuff like that. It doesn't mean anything.

FILM STUDENT #2
It means Linklater shot for twelve years, man. Twelve years. Nobody scares their roommate for twelve years.

Miles listens without turning around. His face: cataloguing. Filing. This is what he does instead of belonging anywhere — he collects the city like evidence for a case he hasn't named yet.

The waitress passes. Miles catches her eye.

MILES
Can I get a slice of the pie? Whatever kind.

WAITRESS
Whatever kind is cherry.

MILES
Whatever kind is great.

EXT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — ROOM 24 — LATER — NIGHT

Miles on the concrete walkway outside his door, back against the wall, legs out. Below in the parking lot, a COUPLE, 40s, argue quietly beside a Nissan with everything they own in it, the argument long past anger into logistics.

Miles's phone BUZZES.

INSERT — PHONE: FaceTime request — "JUNEBUG."

Miles looks at it. Hesitates — checks himself in the black mirror of the screen, actually rehearses a face — then answers, holding the phone so only wall shows behind him.

ON SCREEN: JUNE CALDER, 11, gap-toothed, in pajamas, her face too close to the camera the way kids hold phones. Behind her, a grandmother's floral wallpaper.

JUNE (ON PHONE)
Why is it dark where you are?

MILES
It's dark where everyone is. It's night.

JUNE (ON PHONE)
It's not dark in your room at school. You have the lamp with the green thing.

MILES
(a half-second; she is eleven and she is already the only detective in this family)
I'm outside. Looking at stars.

JUNE (ON PHONE)
(suspicious)
You hate outside.

MILES
I'm growing as a person. What do you want, June?

JUNE (ON PHONE)
(instantly down to business)
Okay so Grandma's TV only has cable so I'm editing on the iPad, and I need to know if skeletons should scream when the wave hits or if it's scarier if they're quiet.

MILES
(without hesitation; this is clearly a serious ongoing consultancy)
Quiet. Screaming is for people who think they can still fix it. Skeletons know.

JUNE (ON PHONE)
(nodding slowly, absorbing this like scripture; writing it down somewhere off-screen)
"Skeletons know." Okay. And you're coming home Saturday?

MILES
(beat)
Yeah.

JUNE (ON PHONE)
Because Mom said Saturday and I planned the premiere for Sunday. There's a program. I made a program.

MILES
I'll be there.

JUNE (ON PHONE)
(holding a piece of paper up to the camera, too close, unreadable, trembling with self-importance)
Assigned seats.

MILES
Wouldn't dream of sitting anywhere else.

She hangs up first — she always hangs up first — and the screen goes home-screen, and Miles is alone again on the walkway with his rehearsed face slowly coming off, like tape.

Below, the couple by the Nissan have stopped arguing. The man has his forehead on the roof of the car. The woman rubs his back, once, twice, and stops, and leaves her hand there.

Miles watches. The neon from the liquor store ticks red, blue, red.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. CAFECITO ORGÁNICO ADJACENT COFFEE SHOP — SILVER LAKE — MORNING

SUPER: "WEDNESDAY"

Reclaimed wood. Edison bulbs. Fourteen laptops, thirteen of them open to screenplays. A BARISTA with a mustache from another century pulls shots with the gravity of a surgeon.

Miles at the counter, reading the menu board, which describes a coffee's tasting notes at greater length than his school described Sam's death.

MILES
Just a coffee. Regular.

BARISTA
Drip's a single-origin Honduran today. Notes of persimmon and brown butter.

MILES
Does it taste like coffee?

BARISTA
(considering the question honestly)
Toward the end.

Miles pays — $4.50, counts it out in cash — and finds the last table. Around him, a symphony of typing. He opens the Didion, actually reads a page this time. Looks up.

At the next table: a MAN, 30s, headshot-handsome, running lines with himself, mouthing both parts of a scene, doing a small contained version of crying, then checking himself in his phone's front camera, then doing it again. No one looks. This is a library and that is studying.

Beside him, a WOMAN, 20s, holds her phone at arm's length above her avocado toast, adjusting the plate twice before shooting. She reviews the photo, applies a filter — that 2014 haze, everything slightly faded like a memory of itself — types, posts, sets the phone face down, and then does not eat the toast. Just looks out the window.

Miles watches her not eat the toast. She feels it, turns. This is LU — TALLULAH BECK, 23, Ohio pretty, sharp under the softness, an American Apparel name tag half-visible in her tote.

LU
It's cold anyway. If you're judging.

MILES
I wasn't —

LU
You were cataloguing. That's worse. Judging at least means you care.

Miles closes the Didion.

MILES
Why photograph it if you're not going to eat it?

LU
(matter-of-fact, no shame anywhere in it)
Because the girl who eats breakfast here books commercial work, and I can't afford to be her and eat her breakfast in the same month. So I split it. She eats. I post.

Miles absorbs this like a transmission from another civilization.

MILES
That's the most honest thing anyone's said to me in four months.

LU
(gathering her stuff; clocking him fully now — the age, the duffel-creased clothes, the paying-in-cash)
How old are you?

MILES
Nineteen.

LU
(putting on her sunglasses)
No.

MILES
Seventeen.

LU
There he is.
(standing; a decision arriving on her face, some mix of boredom and kindness and wanting an audience)
I have an audition at eleven in the Valley and my scene partner canceled. You read flat and dead — I can tell just from talking to you — which is perfect, because the casting guy hates acting. Come read the off-camera lines and I'll buy you actual food.

MILES
Why would I do that?

LU
(already walking)
Because you're seventeen with a duffel bag tan and nowhere to be. Come on.

INT. LU'S CAR — HONDA CIVIC — MOVING — THE 101 NORTH — DAY

A car that is 30% car, 70% closet. Dry cleaning on the back hooks, headshots in the footwell — LU BECK smiling in four different personalities. The Cahuenga Pass, then the Valley opening up below, flat and infinite and shimmering.

LU
(driving; sunglasses; coaching)
Okay. The scene: I'm a young mom whose husband is cheating, and you're reading the husband. It's for a pilot presentation that will never air. The line readings don't matter. What matters is my face while you talk. Your whole job is to be boring enough that they watch my face.

MILES
I can be boring.

LU
Don't oversell it.

Miles flips through the sides — three pages, marked up in three colors of ink.

MILES
You've done this scene before.

LU
I've done this scene nine times this year. Different shows. It's always the wife finding out. That's the role for my — 
(she does quote-fingers on the wheel)
— "type." I've found out my husband was cheating on four networks. I'm great at it. I find out better than anyone in this town.

She says it bright and fast, comedy-fast, but the last sentence lands somewhere real, and she hears it land, and turns up the radio — a synthy indie thing, all reverb and yearning, the exact sound of this year — before the silence can attach.

INT. CASTING OFFICE — NORTH HOLLYWOOD — WAITING ROOM — DAY

Folding chairs down a beige hallway. SEVEN WOMEN who all look approximately like Lu, each in the same "young mom" costume — soft cardigan, minimal makeup — silently mouthing the same lines. A signup sheet on a clipboard. Somewhere, air conditioning that only makes noise.

Miles and Lu sit against the wall. Miles looks down the row of seven versions of her.

MILES
(low)
Does it bother you? That everyone's —

LU
(not lowering her voice at all)
The same? No. See her —
(a tiny nod at one)
— she'll go too big. Cries every time. And her — she'll go too small because someone once told her "less is more" and it ruined her life. I go exactly medium. Medium is money.

A CASTING ASSISTANT with an iPad appears at the door.

CASTING ASSISTANT
Tallulah Beck?

Lu stands. Instantly — visibly — she becomes forty percent softer. Her shoulders round. Her chin drops. Young Mom enters the building and Lu goes somewhere else entirely. It happens in a single step. Miles sees the whole exchange, and it unsettles him more than anything on Sunset did last night.

INT. CASTING OFFICE — AUDITION ROOM — CONTINUOUS

A camera on a tripod. A CASTING DIRECTOR, 50s, who has seen everything and retained none of it, eating almonds from a Ziploc. Miles on a stool beside the camera with the sides.

CASTING DIRECTOR
(not looking up)
Whenever.

MILES
(reading; flat and dead, as instructed)
"I don't know what you want me to say. It was one time. It didn't mean anything."

And LU — Miles's POV, which is the camera's POV — receives the line. Her face does something in four seconds that Miles could not do with a full page: the news landing, being refused, landing anyway, and then — the medium part, the money part — being put away for the sake of a child who is somewhere offstage in the fiction. It's small and complete and genuinely good, and nobody in the room reacts at all.

CASTING DIRECTOR (CONT'D)
(chewing)
Great. Thanks. We'll be in touch through your reps.

LU
(bright; forty percent softer)
Thank you so much for seeing me.

INT. IN-N-OUT BURGER — NORTH HOLLYWOOD — DAY

Red palms on the cups. Lu, back to full voltage, demolishes a Double-Double with the appetite of a woman who has skipped the breakfast she photographs. Miles works on his, watching her.

MILES
You were really good. In there.

LU
(mouth full)
I know.

MILES
Like — actually good. That's the part I don't get. If you can do that, why doesn't —

LU
Because eleven hundred women in this zip code can do that. Talent's the cover charge, babe. It gets you in the door of a room with no chairs.
(she steals his fries; gestures at him with one)
Question is what YOU'RE doing. Seventeen, cash, motel — I've seen this movie. It ends at a bus station or a hospital.

MILES
It's four days. My mom thinks school ends Saturday. It's not a runaway thing, it's —
(he searches; and lands, accidentally, on the truth)
— it's a gap. I found a gap where nobody's watching, and I wanted to see what I'd do in it.

Lu stops chewing. Looks at him — really looks, for the first time.

LU
(quieter)
And what do you do in it?

MILES
(beat)
So far I watch other people.

LU
(going back to the fries; the moment closing like water)
Yeah. That's this whole town. Forty square miles of people watching other people to figure out how to be one.
(then, deciding something)
There's a party tonight. Beachwood Canyon. My roommate's agent's client's house — don't ask me to diagram it. Come. You want to see the terrarium, I'll show you the terrarium.

EXT. BEACHWOOD CANYON — HOLLYWOOD HILLS — NIGHT

A mid-century house cantilevered over the city. Below: LOS ANGELES AT NIGHT, the full carpet of it, ten million lights to the curve of the earth. The kind of view that gets photographed and never gets seen.

INT. HILLS HOUSE — PARTY — NIGHT

Sixty people, all between 22 and 35, all lit beautifully by someone else's success. A DJ plays tasteful electronic. A pool glows outside like a landing pad.

Miles moves through it behind Lu, holding a Solo cup of something he isn't drinking. The film gives us the party in long takes, conversations drifting past:

A GUY, 26, to a semicircle:

PARTY GUY #1
— so we don't even call it a web series anymore, we call it "premium digital," and the second we said "premium digital" the money changed —

A WOMAN, 29, to another woman, both nodding:

PARTY WOMAN #1
— he's blowing up on Vine, which — okay, six seconds, whatever, laugh — but brands pay him more for six seconds than my dad made in a month —

Two MEN by the pool:

PARTY GUY #2
It's called Snapchat. It deletes.

PARTY GUY #3
Why would you want it to delete?

PARTY GUY #2
(looking out at the view; a long pause; almost to himself)
Man, some days that's ALL I want.

And everywhere, past every shoulder: eyes flicking to the door whenever it opens. The whole room in a permanent low-grade scan for someone more useful than whoever they're talking to. Miles clocks it — the over-the-shoulder glance — happening in every conversation, a party-wide tic, until it stops being funny and becomes the loneliest thing he's ever stood inside.

LU
(materializing; handing him a water; reading his face instantly)
You found the thing.

MILES
Nobody's actually here.

LU
Everybody's here. Nobody's PRESENT. Different problem.
(scanning the room herself — and catching herself doing the over-the-shoulder scan mid-sentence; owning it with a grimace)
See? It's in the water.

A HOST-ADJACENT MAN, 30s, blazer over a T-shirt, materializes at Lu's elbow with the smoothness of a man who is always mid-approach.

BLAZER MAN
Lu. Who's the young man?

LU
(without missing a beat)
My cousin. Visiting from Ohio. He's thinking about USC film school.

BLAZER MAN
(to Miles, instantly, warmly, horribly)
Love that. LOVE that. What's your story? Everyone's got a story. Thirty seconds — go.

And the party seems to quiet slightly, or maybe just in Miles's ears. His thirty seconds. The man is actually waiting, actually looking at him, and this is the only kind of being-seen this room knows how to do.

MILES
(a beat; then, evenly)
I got expelled from boarding school for stealing a memorial plaque with my dead best friend's name spelled wrong on it, and my mom doesn't know yet, and I'm staying at a motel on Sunset where the ice machine's been broken since a nonspecific earthquake.

Silence. Two seconds. Three.

BLAZER MAN
(nodding slowly; then, with total sincerity)
That's a GREAT logline. Who's repping you?

He drifts off toward the door, which has just opened. Lu looks at Miles. Miles looks at Lu.

LU
(quietly; a kind of respect)
You told him the truth.

MILES
It's the only thing here nobody recognizes.

EXT. HILLS HOUSE — DECK — NIGHT

Miles alone at the rail with the water. The city below, all of it, going forever. Ten million lights and he can name maybe four of them.

Lu joins him. They stand a moment. The party behind the glass is a silent film.

LU
(looking at the view)
First year I was here, I drove up to a spot like this every time I didn't book something. Which was a lot of driving. I'd look at all that and think: somewhere down there is the version of me that works. I just have to find her and put her on.
(beat)
Four years in — you want the secret? There's no her. There's just this. You do the face until the face does you.

MILES
(looking at the lights)
That's the thing I'm afraid of.

LU
(turning to him; not unkind; the realest she's been all day)
No. You're afraid it's ALREADY happened. That's why you watch everybody — you're checking their seams to find your own.
(she finishes her drink)
Fair warning, from the future: everyone's got seams, babe. The only people without them are the ones who stopped taking the costume off.

She heads back inside — and at the door, reflexively, she checks over her shoulder. Catches herself. Gives Miles a little wave that means: see?

Miles stays at the rail. Below him, Los Angeles glitters like the world's largest unanswered question.

He takes out his phone. Opens the camera. Frames the view — the shot everyone takes, the shot the internet is made of.

Doesn't take it.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — ROOM 24 — LATE MORNING

SUPER: "THURSDAY"

Miles asleep in his clothes on top of the floral spread. The plaque on the nightstand catches the late sun. His phone BUZZES on the carpet where it fell.

INSERT — PHONE: "MOM": "Dean's office called Grandma's house?? Trying to reach me. Prob about pickup logistics. Everything ok?"

Miles, one eye open, looks at the message for a long time. Types: "yeah they're disorganized. all handled." Deletes "all handled." Types "don't worry about it." Deletes that too. Sends just: "yeah."

He lies back. The ceiling. The hum.

MILES
(to the plaque; flat)
Don't say anything.

EXT. SUNSET JUNCTION — SILVER LAKE — DAY

Miles walks past the reservoir crowd — joggers, strollers, a man walking two greyhounds in matching sweaters. December sun, seventy-two degrees, everyone in beanies anyway because it's December somewhere.

He stops outside a RECORD STORE: "PERMANENT HIGH FIDELITY — NEW & USED." A hand-lettered sign in the window: "NO, WE DON'T HAVE THAT. YES, WE HAVE SOMETHING BETTER."

INT. PERMANENT HIGH FIDELITY — RECORD STORE — CONTINUOUS

Crates. That smell — cardboard and dust and forty years of other people's Saturdays. Two customers flip vinyl with the focus of scholars.

Behind the counter, on a stool, reading a paperback with a torn cover: WREN, 19, dark-eyed, self-contained, a film-school thrift-store aesthetic that is somehow the only outfit in Los Angeles that isn't trying. She doesn't look up when the door chimes. She doesn't look up for anybody.

Miles flips through a crate. Then another. He is aware of her the way you're aware of weather changing. Finally, carrying a record he grabbed mostly as a passport, he approaches the counter.

MILES
How much is —

WREN
(not looking up from the book)
You don't want that.

MILES
I don't?

WREN
That's a 2011 repress with brickwalled mastering. It's for people who want to own the album, not hear it.
(she turns a page)
Original pressing's in the bin under it. Four dollars more. Sounds like a door opening into 1972.

MILES
(beat)
How do you know I wasn't buying it to own it?

WREN
(finally looking up; assessing him in one flat pass)
Because you flipped past forty records without checking prices and picked the one closest to the register. You're not buying music. You're buying a conversation.

A silence. Caught. Completely caught. Miles sets the record on the counter.

MILES
Okay. What's the conversation cost?

WREN
(going back to the book; but there's a milligram of a smile now)
Four dollars more. Same as the pressing.

INT. PERMANENT HIGH FIDELITY — LISTENING STATION — LATER

A turntable and two mismatched headphones at the back. Miles under one can, Wren — on break, technically — under the other, sharing the cord's radius, both facing the wall like it's a movie. The record spins. We hear what they hear: something 1972 and warm, a door opening.

WREN
(eyes on the wall)
So what are you? NYU kid home for break? You've got the "I read" thing going on but your shoes have never worked a day.

MILES
I'm between institutions.

WREN
(turning her head; the phrase earning one raised eyebrow)
Expelled.

MILES
Why does everyone in this city just SAY the thing —

WREN
Because it's a company town and the company is watching people. What'd you do?

And here it comes — the bit. We've seen the shape of it now: the shrug loading, the deadpan pre-assembling, "solid brass, though" waiting in the chamber. Miles opens his mouth —

WREN (CONT'D)
(back to the wall; mild; devastating)
And don't do a routine. I watch four customers an hour do routines. Just say it or don't.

The bit dies in his throat. Long pause. The record turns.

MILES
(quietly; no shrug anywhere)
My best friend died in March. Car accident, coming back from a show in Echo Park — a show I bailed on, which is either relevant or it isn't, I've spent nine months not deciding.
(beat)
The school put up a bench with a brass plaque and spelled his name wrong. And everyone walked past it all year like it was fine. So last month I took a screwdriver and I un-put-it-up. It's on my nightstand at a motel. I don't know what I'm doing with it. That's the actual answer. There's no routine version.

Wren doesn't say sorry. Doesn't touch his arm. She looks at the wall a while, with him, both of them inside the same headphone cord.

WREN
(finally)
What was the show?

MILES
(thrown)
What?

WREN
The show he was coming back from. What band?

MILES
(a beat; nobody has ever asked him a single specific question about it; the specificity almost undoes him)
Some four-piece from Highland Park. They had one EP on Bandcamp. Sam said they sounded like — 
(and he smiles, wrecked, remembering)
— "like The Cure got a day job." He said that in the last text he ever sent me.

WREN
(nodding slowly; then, standing, decision made, pulling off the headphones)
Okay. I get off at six.

MILES
What happens at six?

WREN
(already walking back to the counter)
We go find out if they still play.

EXT. ECHO PARK — SUNSET BOULEVARD — EVENING (MAGIC HOUR)

And here the film spends its title. Wren and Miles walk east on Sunset as the light does the thing Los Angeles light does for eleven minutes a day — gold pouring down the boulevard sideways, palm shadows forty feet long, every stucco wall suddenly a Rothko, and none of it lasts.

They walk and talk in one unbroken take, trading sentences with the ease of people who skipped three stages of knowing each other.

WREN
— film school's a scam, I take actual film classes at LACC for nothing while the USC kids pay two hundred grand to network with each other's dads —

MILES
So what do you want to make?

WREN
Documentaries nobody asked for. There's a man on my block who's been repainting the same fence for six years. Every day. Same fence. I've got forty hours of him.

MILES
Is it good?

WREN
(considering it honestly)
It's either the best thing ever shot or it's forty hours of a fence. There's no third option. That's why it's worth doing.

EXT. THE ECHO — CLUB ENTRANCE — NIGHT

A small marquee. Tonight's bill: three bands nobody's heard of. Wren scans the names. Shakes her head.

WREN
Not them. But —
(she's on her phone; 2014 detective work: Bandcamp, a defunct Tumblr, a Facebook page)
— their old Facebook says the singer bartends Thursdays at a place in Thai Town.

MILES
It's Thursday.

WREN
It's Thursday.

INT. DIVE BAR — THAI TOWN — NIGHT

Red vinyl, Christmas lights that never come down, a jukebox glowing in the corner. Behind the bar: the SINGER, 27, tattooed forearms, drying glasses. Wren and Miles at the rail — Wren's presence somehow neutralizing all questions about Miles's age.

WREN
You used to play in a band. Four-piece, Highland Park, one EP.

SINGER
(wary; wiping)
That was a hundred years ago. We broke up in like April.

MILES
(the date landing on him — April; one month after)
Why?

SINGER
(shrugging)
Why does anyone. Drummer moved to Austin. Bassist got a girlfriend with opinions.
(beat; squinting at them)
Why do two children care?

MILES
(and he doesn't do a routine; watch him not do it)
My friend saw you in March. At the Echo. It was the last thing he ever did. He texted me from the show that you sounded like The Cure got a day job.

The singer stops wiping the glass.

A long moment. The Christmas lights. The jukebox hum.

SINGER
(quietly)
That's the best review we ever got.

He sets down the glass. Looks at the jukebox. Then he walks over to it, feeds it quarters from the tip jar, and punches in numbers from memory.

SINGER (CONT'D)
We put the EP on there. Bribe the owner with free shifts. Track's called "Reseda Snow."

The song starts — reverb-drowned guitar, a drum machine, a voice like someone singing to you from the next room so as not to wake anyone. It IS The Cure with a day job. It's also, played in a mostly empty bar in Thai Town on a Thursday, the closest thing to a memorial service Sam ever got.

Miles sits very still and listens to the whole thing. Wren watches Miles listen. The singer leans on the bar and looks at nothing.

Three people, one song, nobody performing anything.

The track ends. The bar hum returns.

MILES
(to the singer; barely)
Thanks.

SINGER
(picking the glass back up; gruff; kind)
Tell your friend we said hey.

EXT. ECHO PARK — WREN'S BUILDING — ROOFTOP — NIGHT

A four-story walk-up roof: tar paper, two lawn chairs, a dead hibachi, string lights that reach the first chair only. The downtown skyline in the middle distance, lit like an aquarium.

Wren and Miles in the lawn chairs. A shared bag of gas-station peanut M&Ms between them, resting on the arm of her chair like a treaty.

WREN
You know what your problem is?

MILES
People keep telling me tonight, so — go, sure, join in.

WREN
You think noticing everything is the same as being honest. It's not. It's a hiding place with a view.

Miles opens his mouth. Closes it. The skyline glitters.

MILES
(finally)
Sam used to just — be places. Fully. He'd walk into a room and like it. No angles. I used to study him like a foreign film.
(beat)
When he died I think I decided if I never fully showed up anywhere again, nothing could ever —

He stops. The sentence knows where it's going and refuses to arrive. Wren doesn't finish it for him. She eats an M&M. The city hums.

WREN
(eventually; looking at the skyline)
My mom died when I was fourteen. So I'm not going to say the things people say.
(beat)
I'll just tell you the one true thing I got out of it: the missing doesn't shrink. Everybody waits for it to shrink. It doesn't. You just — build a bigger life around it, so it's not the only thing in the room.
(she rattles the M&M bag; practical; unsentimental)
Your life right now is one room and the missing is wall to wall. That's the whole diagnosis. That'll be four dollars.

Miles laughs — one real laugh, out before he can inspect it. And in the quiet after, he looks at her — string lights, tar paper, the exact face of the only person in this city who has asked him a specific question — and the film lets the moment open: the lean-in available, the night willing.

Miles doesn't take it. Not out of fear — out of something more careful. Wren sees him not take it, and sees why. It's the most honest thing he's done all week, and they both know it, and neither says it.

WREN (CONT'D)
(standing; stretching; the moment folded neatly and put away)
Get home safe, between-institutions.

MILES
That's the plan.

It is not the plan. There is no plan.

INT. FROLIC ROOM — HOLLYWOOD BOULEVARD — LATER THAT NIGHT

The neon sign outside like a migraine in a good suit. Inside: a shoebox of a bar, red booths, a mural of dead celebrities watching from the wall. Miles — riding the night, not ready for the motel — nurses a Coke at the bar. The BARTENDER left him alone after one ID glance and a Coke order; the Coke is his cover charge.

Two stools down: GIDEON PRICE, late 40s, in a blazer of genuine quality gone soft at the cuffs. Handsome the way a demolished landmark is handsome. Three drinks in, holding court for no one.

GIDEON
(to the mural, to the bartender, to the air)
You know what this bar had in 1998? A PAYPHONE. And I was ON it, nightly. People called ME back.

He notices Miles. The way lonely performers notice audiences.

GIDEON (CONT'D)
You know who I am?

MILES
No.

GIDEON
(delighted; wounded; both)
GOOD. Honest child. Everyone else pretends they're not sure. "Were you on that show?" I WAS the show, from '89 to '94. I was on lunchboxes. There is a landfill in Nevada with my face on it, ten thousand times.

MILES
What show?

GIDEON
(waving it away grandly)
Doesn't matter. It's not on the streaming things. I checked. I check monthly. When it's not on the streaming things —
(he taps his temple)
— it only exists in here. And in the lunchbox landfill.

He slides down a stool. The bartender clocks it — clocks Miles — keeps drying glasses, keeps watch. A dive bar's whole immune system in one glance.

GIDEON (CONT'D)
What are you? Actor? You've got a face for it. Sad and symmetrical.

MILES
I'm not anything yet.

GIDEON
(pointing at him; too loud; genuinely moved)
THAT — is the last honest career description in this town. "Not anything yet." God. Frame that.
(leaning in; the whiskey doing the talking now, but underneath it something true)
Let me tell you what nobody told me at your age. They will hand you a self. This town — it hands you one, fitted, flattering, and it feels like being loved. And you'll wear it, and wear it —
(he looks down at his soft cuffs)
— and one day they ask for it back. And you go looking for whatever you were before they fitted you, and kid — 
(he smiles; the smile is the worst thing in the movie so far)
— there's nothing back there. I checked. I check monthly.

Miles sits very still. The mural of dead celebrities watches.

GIDEON (CONT'D)
(brightening horribly, the turn too fast)
I've got the residuals coming next month, and a manager who's — she's basically still my manager — you drink, you should come up, I'm around the corner, I've got the actual PUPPET from the show, you have to see the puppet —

MILES
(standing; a twenty on the bar; the oldest instinct finally firing)
I gotta go.

GIDEON
(and for one second the performance drops entirely — no charm, no volume, just a man on a stool in the middle of his life)
Yeah.
(beat)
Yeah, that's the right answer, kid. That's the whole test. You passed.

He turns back to his drink. The bartender gives Miles a fractional nod: good. Miles pushes out the door.

EXT. HOLLYWOOD BOULEVARD — NIGHT — CONTINUOUS

The stars on the sidewalk with names nobody reads. A COSTUMED CHARACTER — a superhero, mask under his arm, on break — smokes alone against a wall, cape moving in the night wind off the boulevard.

Miles walks fast, hands jammed in pockets, Gideon's sentence chasing him: "there's nothing back there."

He walks past a WAX MUSEUM. Past a tour van promising DEAD CELEBRITY HOMES. Past a group of TOURISTS photographing the sidewalk, the literal ground, because it has names on it.

He stops at the corner of Hollywood and Vine because his body stops. Looks around at all of it — the lights, the names, the costumes, the vans.

And for the first time in the film, MILES'S FACE ISN'T CATALOGUING. It's just seventeen, and lost, and eleven o'clock at night, sixteen miles from a mother who thinks he's at school and four hundred yards from a bar where his own future just bought him a Coke's worth of prophecy.

He takes out his phone. Scrolls to "MOM." Thumb over the call button.

The screen's clock: 11:47 PM.

He doesn't call. He puts it away. But the film saw him almost do it, and that's new.

INT. METRO RED LINE — MOVING — NIGHT

Fluorescent light. Nearly empty car rocking through the tunnel. Miles in a corner seat. Across the car, a NIGHT-SHIFT WORKER in scrubs sleeps sitting up with her lanyard still on, and a BUSKER with a guitar case rides in silence, off duty, looking at his own reflection in the black window.

Miles looks at his reflection too. The tunnel lights strobe across it.

HOLD.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — ROOM 24 — MORNING

SUPER: "FRIDAY"

Gray light. The first overcast day — December remembering itself. Miles sits on the edge of the bed, dressed, still. The plaque is in his hands. He turns it over. Turns it back.

"SAMUEL ORTEGAS '15."

He wraps it in the T-shirt. Puts it in his jacket. Not the duffel — the jacket. Today it travels.

EXT. NORTH HOLLYWOOD STATION — ORANGE LINE PLATFORM — MORNING

Miles transfers from the Red Line to the Orange Line busway. The Valley under cloud: flatter, wider, humbler. The billboard faces out here advertise personal injury lawyers instead of shows.

INT./EXT. METRO ORANGE LINE BUS — MOVING — MORNING

Miles watches the Valley scroll: body shops, churches in former banks, a hundred small businesses named after somebody's daughter. A pair of ABUELAS across the aisle discuss something hilarious in Spanish. A TEENAGER naps against the window with his skateboard held to his chest like a rifle at rest.

It's the least glamorous ride of the movie and the film shoots it the most tenderly.

EXT. RESEDA — RESIDENTIAL STREET — LATE MORNING

A block of one-story postwar houses, chain-link and rosebushes, old RVs in side yards. Miles walks it slow, checking house numbers — but his body already knows the way. He's been here a hundred times. Just not since March.

He stops in front of a pale yellow house. A wind chime. A statue of the Virgin in a bathtub shrine, garden kept. On the porch, a rack of drying chilies.

In the driveway: a 2003 CIVIC with a faded parking permit sticker from Camino School on the windshield.

Sam's car. Repaired. Washed. Parked. Kept.

Miles stands at the gate a long time. Long enough that we think he might not. His hand goes to the latch — and the front door opens first.

LUCIA ORTEGA, 50s, work clothes, reading glasses pushed up in her hair, stands in the doorway. A beat as she processes him — and then her whole body does something between a flinch and an embrace, both at once, frozen in the door frame.

LUCIA
Milo.

Nobody has called him that in the entire film. His name in this house was always Milo.

MILES
Hi, Mrs. Ortega.

LUCIA
(already turning inside; not a question)
You eat?

INT. ORTEGA HOUSE — KITCHEN — DAY

Small, immaculate, warm. Photos on the refrigerator under magnets: SAM ORTEGA, 17 in the most recent ones — big grin, a face built for liking rooms — as a toddler in others, in a First Communion suit in one. A calendar on the wall still turned to MARCH.

The film clocks the calendar and says nothing.

Lucia sets a plate in front of Miles — reheated pozole, tortillas, the whole liturgy — and sits across with coffee she doesn't drink.

LUCIA
Your mama said you were away at the school still. When I saw her at the Vons in the summer.

MILES
(carefully)
I was. I'm... between semesters.

LUCIA
(looking at him over the glasses; a mother's radar pinging once, softly, then letting it go)
Mm.

He eats. He's genuinely hungry — days of diner food and gas station M&Ms — and the eating gives them both somewhere to put their eyes. On the wall: a framed photo of SAM AND MILES, 15, in matching band T-shirts, sunburned, at some outdoor show, Sam mid-laugh, Miles caught for once mid-laugh too.

MILES
(nodding at the driveway; the question he came with; almost steady)
You fixed the car.

LUCIA
(stirring the coffee she isn't drinking)
His tío fixed it. It took him four months. I told him, Beto, why, nobody's going to —
(she stops; restarts; the practiced route around the hole)
He said a car shouldn't sit broken. So now it sits fixed.

Beat.

LUCIA (CONT'D)
Sundays I start the engine so the battery keeps. I sit in it while it runs. Ten minutes.
(she looks at Miles; no drama; just the plain report of a fellow resident of the country he lives in)
It still smells like him. The stupid coconut thing on the mirror. I don't drive it anywhere. Where would it go?

Miles has stopped eating. Now — now, in the yellow house, in front of the only other person for whom the missing is wall to wall — he takes the T-shirt bundle from his jacket and sets it on the table and unwraps it.

The plaque. Brass. "SAMUEL ORTEGAS '15 — FOREVER IN OUR HEARTS."

Lucia looks at it a long time. Puts her reading glasses down from her hair. Reads it properly.

LUCIA (CONT'D)
(quietly)
They spelled it wrong.

MILES
For eleven months. By a pond nobody sits at. I walked past it every day waiting for one person to notice, and nobody — 
(his voice going; he presses on)
— they had a ceremony, Mrs. Ortega. Catering. The headmaster said "Samuel touched us all" and he called him Samuel, nobody ever called him Samuel, and then everyone had lemon bars.
(beat)
So I took it. And they expelled me. And I've been carrying it around Los Angeles for four days like an idiot because I couldn't figure out what it was FOR, and then this morning I figured out it was for you. It should be somewhere that spells him right. Even if the plaque doesn't. You could —
(he runs out of plan exactly here)
— I don't know. I don't know what you do with it. I'm sorry. Maybe I shouldn't have —

LUCIA
(picking it up; weighing it in both hands; interrupting him without raising her voice)
Milo.

He stops.

LUCIA (CONT'D)
You got thrown out of that school for this?

MILES
(beat)
Yes, ma'am.

And Lucia Ortega starts to laugh. It ambushes her — a real laugh, from the floor of herself, tears arriving in it midway and the laugh continuing anyway, both systems running at once, and she puts one hand flat on the table to ride it out.

LUCIA
(through it; wiping her eyes with her wrist)
He would have LOVED this. You know that? A brass plaque with the wrong name and you, walking around Hollywood with it in your coat like a — like a lunatic —
(she catches her breath; holds the plaque to her chest, both arms, the laugh settling into something else entirely)
— ay, Milo. You dumb, sweet boy. You're the only one who did anything the right size.

Silence in the kitchen. The wind chime outside. Miles looks at the table.

MILES
(the thing he actually came to say; nine months in transit; barely audible)
I was supposed to be in the car.

LUCIA
(gently; she has clearly always known)
I know.

MILES
I bailed to study for a test. A TEST. And if I'd gone, maybe he leaves earlier, or later, or I'm talking and he's not tired, or —

LUCIA
(putting her hand over his; stopping the machine mid-cycle; the authority of the only person on earth entitled to rule on this)
Or you're both gone, and I'm visiting two benches.
(beat)
You want to do the math forever, mijo, that's the one equation nobody solves. I tried. His father tried. You give it years if you want — it takes years, it's happy to take them — and at the end it hands you back the same answer: he's not here, and you are.
(she squeezes his hand once, hard)
And you being here is not a crime. It's just the assignment. It's the worst assignment. And you show up for it anyway — the way you showed up today.

Miles finally cries. Small, contained, seventeen — head down, one hand over his eyes, the other still under hers. Lucia doesn't gather him up. She just keeps her hand where it is and looks at the photos on the refrigerator, and lets the kitchen hold all three of them.

EXT. ORTEGA HOUSE — DRIVEWAY — LATER

Lucia and Miles by the Civic. She opens the passenger door for him. He gets in. She gets in the driver's side. She turns the key — the engine catches, settles into an idle.

They sit in the parked car, engine running, going nowhere. The coconut air freshener sways on the mirror. Miles breathes in. Closes his eyes.

Through the windshield: the pale yellow house, the bathtub Virgin, the chilies drying on the porch. Ten minutes, every Sunday, and today, once, on a Friday, with a passenger.

Neither of them says anything. The scene runs longer than any studio would let it. That's how we know it's the center of the movie.

EXT. RESEDA — BUS STOP — AFTERNOON

Miles waits for the Orange Line, lighter by one plaque. His phone BUZZES. He looks —

INSERT — PHONE: "JUNEBUG": "why is your location off"
Then immediately: "it's been off for 4 days"
Then: "miles."
Then: "i'm 11 not stupid"

Miles stares at the screen. Types nothing. It buzzes again:

INSERT — PHONE: "grandma naps at 2. i have $31 and i know how to use the big bus. tell me where you are or i find you the hard way"

MILES
(out loud, alone, at a bus stop in Reseda; with total sincerity)
Oh no.

EXT. SANTA MONICA PIER — LATE AFTERNOON

Gray ocean, gray sky, the Ferris wheel turning its lights against the overcast like it can fix the weather by itself. Off-season and under-attended: the pier belongs to seagulls, fishermen, and the faithful.

At the rail near the end, holding a churro like a scepter, backpack on both shoulders: JUNE. Beside her, summoned, defeated, holding his own churro he doesn't remember agreeing to buy: MILES.

JUNE
You said the school had a lamp with a green thing and then you were outside and then Dean Whatever called Grandma's landline TWICE.
(she takes a bite; chews; prosecutorial)
I put it together in like ten minutes. Mom's going to put it together on an airplane with no wifi and land already knowing.

MILES
I know.

JUNE
Are you expelled?

MILES
Yes.

JUNE
(nodding; filing it; then, the only question that matters in her jurisdiction)
Are you okay?

And there it is. Four days, a whole city of people asking him what he was, what his story was, what his thirty seconds were — and an eleven-year-old with churro sugar on her jacket is the first person to ask that.

MILES
(the truth; simple; new)
Today? Kind of. First time in a while. Kind of.

JUNE
(accepting the report; looking at the ocean)
Good.
(beat)
Is it because of Sam?

MILES
(beat)
Everything's a little because of Sam.

JUNE
(matter-of-fact, eleven, merciless, precious)
I liked him. He talked to me like a person and he did the thing where he pretended my videos were real movies. Wait —
(she turns; outraged by her own memory)
— he called them FILMS. He said "your films." Nobody says films.

MILES
(looking at the water)
Yeah. He was always saying stuff like that.

The Ferris wheel turns. A fisherman two rails down reels in nothing, checks the hook, casts again — the whole human condition in one gesture, and June watches it like it's programming.

JUNE
Mom lands tomorrow at four.

MILES
I know.

JUNE
Are you going to be home when she gets there? Actually home? Because I can cover for you for like an hour, tops. I fold under direct questioning.

MILES
(a small laugh)
You don't fold.

JUNE
I folded about the fish. The fish died because of me and I folded in four minutes.

MILES
(beat)
The fish died because of you?

JUNE
(staring straight ahead at the ocean)
This is exactly what I'm talking about. I can't live like this.

Miles laughs — the second real laugh of the film, and this one has company: June cracks too, and for a second they're just siblings at a rail, gray ocean, dying light, two churros.

The laugh settles. June leans her head sideways against his arm — too short to reach his shoulder, so it's his arm, and she has to tilt weird to do it, and does it anyway.

JUNE (CONT'D)
(quietly; to the ocean)
Don't disappear like that again. Turn your location on.
(beat)
I don't care where you go. I just want the dot to be somewhere.

Miles looks down at the top of his sister's head. Then out at the Pacific — flat, enormous, indifferent, free — the ocean this movie has been walking toward for four days.

He takes out his phone. Settings. Location: ON.

The dot returns to the map of the world.

MILES
There. I'm a dot.

JUNE
(not lifting her head)
You're THE dot.

The Ferris wheel lights deepen as the gray goes to blue. The film holds the two of them at the rail, small against the water, for a long, long time.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — ROOM 24 — MORNING

SUPER: "SATURDAY"

The duffel, packed, by the door. The room already forgetting him: bed made badly but made, harbor painting straightened for some reason. Miles does a last pass and finds, on the nightstand where the plaque lived, only the clean rectangle of dust around where it stood.

He looks at the rectangle. Four days ago an identical shape was screw holes on a bench.

He wipes the dust away with his sleeve. Some shapes you don't leave behind for the next guy.

INT. GOLD STAR MOTEL — OFFICE — CONTINUOUS

Miles slides the key under the plexiglass. The manager, same stool, same fan, glances up.

MANAGER
Find what you were looking for?

MILES
(honestly)
I don't know. Some of it.

MANAGER
(back to the TV)
That's the good answer. Kids who say "yes" scare me.

EXT. PERMANENT HIGH FIDELITY — RECORD STORE — MORNING

CLOSED sign. Gate half down. Miles cups his hands to the glass — dark inside. He takes out Derek's business card — WRITER / COVERAGE / RIDES — turns it over, and writes on the back in borrowed pen:

INSERT — CARD: "The fence movie is the best thing ever shot. There's no third option. — the conversation you sold for $4"

He wedges it in the gate. Walks. Stops. Comes back, adds one line:

INSERT — CARD: "M. Calder. (that's the name for the credits)"

EXT. MAR VISTA — RESIDENTIAL STREET — LATE AFTERNOON

A modest street south of Venice Boulevard. Bungalows, jacarandas out of bloom, a mailman finishing his route. Miles walks it with the duffel — the walk of a man to his own sentencing.

Ahead: his HOUSE. Small, white, a lemon tree. In the driveway, a sedan with a rental company barcode in the window. Mom's home from the airport.

Miles stops at the gate. Through the front window, lit: DIANE CALDER, 40s, still in travel clothes, standing in the living room with a landline cordless in one hand and a piece of mail in the other. The dean's letter. Open.

She isn't pacing. She isn't yelling into the phone. She's just standing there, reading it again, one hand on the back of a chair, and from the gate, through glass, in silence, it's somehow worse than any version he rehearsed.

June's face appears in the window beside her — spotting Miles at the gate. A frozen beat. Then June holds up one hand: five fingers. Mouths: "I got you five minutes." And vanishes deeper into the house to run whatever interference an 11-year-old runs.

Miles breathes. Opens the gate. The walk to a front door has never been longer in cinema.

INT. CALDER HOUSE — LIVING ROOM — CONTINUOUS

The door opens. Diane turns. Mother and son, across a living room, the dean's letter still in her hand.

A silence with years in it.

DIANE
(not loud; which is the frightening part)
Four days.

MILES
Mom —

DIANE
The school says Tuesday. It is Saturday. I have been in Denver assuming my son was doing final exams, and my son was —
(she looks at the letter; reads the line that has been eating her since the driveway)
— "whereabouts believed to be with family."
(looking up)
Whose family, Miles? Because it wasn't this one.

MILES
I was going to tell you Saturday. Today. I was always coming home today —

DIANE
Where did you SLEEP?

MILES
A motel. On Sunset. I had money, I was careful, I —

DIANE
(the cordless goes down on the table so she can have both hands for this)
You're seventeen. Anything — do you understand me — ANYTHING could have —
(and here the anger's floor gives way and what's under it comes through, which is worse)
I lost — 
(she stops herself. Rebuilds the sentence smaller.)
This family is not big enough to lose anyone else. Not to anything. Not even to four days.

The room rings with it. Miles looks at the carpet. When he finally speaks, it isn't a defense.

MILES
You're right.

DIANE
(thrown; loaded for a fight that isn't coming)
...What?

MILES
You're right. It was selfish. I just —
(and now the thing itself, spoken to his mother for the first time, no bit, no shrug, no brass)
Mom, I couldn't come home and sit in my room and be the expelled kid whose friend is dead. I've been that kid in every room since March. Every adult does the head-tilt. The voice. And I got four days where nobody knew to do the voice, and I took them.
(beat)
I'm not saying it was okay. I'm saying it was that.

Diane looks at her son. And we watch a mother recalculate a year of assumptions in real time — the grades, the silences, the school's tidy phrases — against the plain sentence just handed to her.

DIANE
(finally; quieter)
The school said you vandalized a memorial.

MILES
The school spelled his name wrong on it and never noticed. I took it down and drove it to his mother's house yesterday. She's keeping it.

A long silence.

DIANE
(absorbing this; then, almost against her will)
...They spelled it wrong?

MILES
Eleven months, Mom.

Diane sits down slowly on the arm of the sofa. Looks at the letter in her hand — this official, letterheaded account of her son — then at the actual boy standing in the actual doorway.

DIANE
(setting the letter down; the practical mother resurfacing because someone has to)
You're grounded until the sun burns out. You know that.

MILES
Yeah.

DIANE
Phone location stays on. Forever. I don't care when you're forty.

MILES
June had the same terms.

DIANE
(rubbing her eyes; a broken laugh escaping)
Of course she did.
(then, looking at him; the last item, the real one, delivered like logistics because it's too big to deliver any other way)
Monday we find you a new school. And a — 
(beat)
— someone to talk to. A professional. Non-negotiable. That's the tuition for the four days.

MILES
(and he means it, which surprises even him)
Okay.

DIANE
(standing; smoothing her travel clothes; done — because if she does one more second of this she'll come apart, and dinner won't make itself)
There's a premiere tomorrow, I'm told. Assigned seating.

MILES
I've seen the program. It's a strong lineup.

She crosses to the kitchen. Stops as she passes him. And — not a hug; this family doesn't reload that fast — she puts one hand on the side of his head, holds it there two seconds, looking at him like she's confirming the object is real. Then she's past him, and pots start.

June's head appears around the hallway corner. She holds up her hand again: five fingers. Then slowly folds four down, leaving one.

JUNE
(mouthing)
You owe me.

EXT. GRIFFITH OBSERVATORY — LAWN — SUNDAY — LATE AFTERNOON (MAGIC HOUR)

SUPER: "SUNDAY"

The great white domes. Tourists thinning as the light goes gold. The whole basin below: downtown to the sea, the city laid out like the answer sheet to a test nobody gets to take twice.

On the lawn, on a blanket: MILES and JUNE. Between them, propped on a backpack: the iPad, playing JUNE'S FILM.

INSERT — iPAD SCREEN: stop-motion. A cardboard city by an aluminum-foil sea. Skeletons — the plastic Halloween kind — go about tiny lives: a skeleton waters a plant; a skeleton walks a dog made of erasers. Then the foil sea rises. The wave comes, cardboard buildings tipping frame by frame.

The skeletons don't scream. They stand together at the foil's edge, tiny hands joined with visible loops of thread, and watch it come. Quiet. Because skeletons know.

Then — the last shot — the wave passes, and the skeletons are still there. Wet foil everywhere. Still standing. One waters the plant again.

THE END, in June's handwriting, held up on a piece of cardboard by a skeleton.

June watches Miles watch it. The only review she has ever cared about.

MILES
(long pause; genuinely undone by a Halloween skeleton watering a plant)
June. It's the best film of the year.

JUNE
(exhaling; then, all business)
It's ninety seconds.

MILES
It's the best ninety-second film of the year, and everything else is too long.

JUNE
(lying back on the blanket, hands behind her head, accepting her laurels)
Sam would've called it a film.

MILES
(looking out at the city)
Sam would've made them screen it at school and introduced it for ten minutes.

JUNE
(giggling)
He WOULD.

The light is doing the eleven-minute thing now — the whole basin gold, the ocean a white line at the far edge, every window in Los Angeles briefly on fire, ten million lives lit at once.

Miles takes out his phone. Opens the camera. Frames the view — the city, the light, the shot he has refused all week.

Then he turns the phone around, stretches his arm — and takes the picture the OTHER way: him and June, squinting, the city behind them small and out of focus. A terrible photo. Half his head is out of frame. June is mid-blink.

He looks at it.

Keeps it.

JUNE (CONT'D)
(eyes closed, face to the sun)
Send it to Mom.

MILES
(typing)
Sending it to Mom.

INSERT — PHONE: the photo, sent to "MOM." Below it he types: "at the observatory with the director. home by 7." A beat. Then the typing bubble from her side. Then just: a heart.

Miles puts the phone away. Lies back next to his sister on the blanket, city noise far below, the dome white above them, the light finishing.

JUNE
(sleepily; apropos of nothing; eleven)
When I make my real movie, you can help. You notice stuff. You'd be good at the noticing job.

MILES
(eyes on the sky; a smile arriving with no audience to perform it for — the first unwatched smile of the film)
Yeah. I'm thinking about going into noticing.

The gold goes. The blue comes. The city lights rise to meet the dark the way they do every single night, whether anyone earns it or not.

The two of them stay on the blanket, small on the lawn, the observatory keeping watch behind them.

We pull back — the lawn, the domes, the hills, the whole impossible city —

And hold.

FADE OUT.

THE END

/* FINAL NOTE: No epilogue. We don't see the new school, the therapist's office, or Wren's reply — though Wren's reply exists, and if the studio insists, it's a single text over the first credit: a photo of the business card taped to the register, and the words "fence movie starts monday. you're listed as a producer. it pays nothing." Roll the rest of the credits over "Reseda Snow." */